      <listPerson>
         <person xml:id="person_421">
            <persName xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">
               <forename type="first">Sigmund</forename>
               <surname>Zois</surname>
            </persName>
            <birth when="1747"/>
            <death when="1819"/>
            <note>Wealthy mining magnate in what is now Slovenia. A influential intellectual  and keen amateur mineralogist.</note>
         </person>
         <person xml:id="person_143">
            <persName xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">
               <forename type="first">Benjamin</forename>
               <surname>Thompson</surname>
            </persName>
            <birth when="1753"/>
            <death when="1814"/>
            <note>Born in Massachusetts, he served in the British and Bavarian armies. Knighted by George III in 1787, the Elector of Bavaria created him Reichsgraf von Rumford of the Holy Roman Empire in 1792. His appointment in the late 1790s as Bavarian ambassador to London created a minor diplomatic incident, during which he helped establish and manage the Royal Institution, in the course of which he appointed Davy to lecture there. Later he married Lavoisier's widow and lived unhappily ever after. FRSL.</note>
         </person>
         <person xml:id="person_784">
            <persName xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">
               <forename type="first">Daniel Gabriel</forename>
               <surname>Fahrenheit</surname>
            </persName>
            <birth when="1686"/>
            <death when="1736"/>
            <note>German physicist, inventor, and scientific instrument maker, who invented the mercury-in-glass thermometer. The temperature scale he proposed is named after him. ForMemRSL.</note>
         </person>
         <person xml:id="person_368">
            <persName xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">
               <forename type="first">Horace Bénédict de</forename>
               <surname>Saussure</surname>
            </persName>
            <birth when="1740"/>
            <death when="1799"/>
            <note>Genevan geologist, meteorologist, physicist, mountaineer and Alpine expolorer. Often referred to as the founder of Alpinism and modern meteorology.</note>
         </person>
         <person xml:id="person_349">
            <persName xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">
               <forename type="first">Jöns Jacob</forename>
               <surname>Berzelius</surname>
            </persName>
            <birth when="1779"/>
            <death when="1848"/>
            <note>Swedish chemist. He discovered the chemical elements cerium and selenium, and was the first to isolate silicon, thorium, titanium, and zirconium. A rival of Davy's whom he met a few times.</note>
         </person>
         <person xml:id="person_183">
            <persName xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">
               <forename type="first">Nickolas</forename>
               <surname>Esterhazy</surname>
            </persName>
            <birth when="1765"/>
            <death when="1833"/>
            <note>Hungarian prince and patron of the arts, especially music. Davy presented him with a copy of Salmonia.</note>
         </person>
