         <place xml:id="place_169">
            <placeName>Mount Vesuvius</placeName>
            <location>
               <geo decls="#WGS84">40.82295082311693,  14.4286697656167</geo>
            </location>
            <note>Mount Vesuvius is a somma-stratovolcano located on the Gulf of Naples in Campania, Italy.</note>
         </place>
      </listPlace>
      <listAnnotation type="miscellaneous">
         <note xml:id="misc_740" type="description">
            <term id="misc_740-term">Rhind</term>
            <gloss id="misc_740-gloss" target="#misc_740-term">
               <p>Unidentified river. The third river at this confluence, besides the Danube and the Inn which Davy mentions is the Ilz.</p>
            </gloss>
         </note>
         <note xml:id="misc_239" type="description">
            <term id="misc_239-term">goitres</term>
            <gloss id="misc_239-gloss" target="#misc_239-term">
               <p>A lump or swelling at the front of the neck and enlargement of the thyroid in the neck which used to affect large parts of the population in the Alpine region, due to a lack of iodine in the Alpine soil and consequently in crops and fruit. Davy sometimes also uses this term to describe geological features.</p>
            </gloss>
         </note>
         <note xml:id="misc_057" type="description">
            <term id="misc_057-term">the Proteus</term>
            <gloss id="misc_057-gloss" target="#misc_057-term">
               <p>Known as the olm, a cave salamandera, which Davy sent specimens of to the natural historian Sir Everard Home.</p>
            </gloss>
         </note>
         <note xml:id="misc_324" type="description">
            <term id="misc_324-term">The Réaumur scale</term>
            <gloss id="misc_324-gloss" target="#misc_324-term">
               <p>A temperature scale for which the melting and boiling points of water are defined as 0 and 80 degrees respectively.</p>
            </gloss>
         </note>
         <note xml:id="misc_744" type="description">
            <term id="misc_744-term">If matter cannot be destroyed/The living mind can never die</term>
            <gloss id="misc_744-gloss" target="#misc_744-term">
               <p>John Davy published these lines as part of a poem in his Memoirs; see Collected Works, vol. 1, p.234.</p>
            </gloss>
         </note>
         <note xml:id="misc_745" type="description">
            <term id="misc_745-term">The things; that glorious on the earth [...] eternal sun arise</term>
            <gloss id="misc_745-gloss" target="#misc_745-term">
               <p>John Davy published these lines as part of a poem in his Memoirs; see Collected Works, vol. 1, p.234. In the first line, John replaces "The"with "All" and transcribes "most" instead of "that".</p>
            </gloss>
         </note>
         <note xml:id="misc_746" type="description">
            <term id="misc_746-term">The transient rainbow tints of heaven</term>
            <gloss id="misc_746-gloss" target="#misc_746-term">
               <p>John Davy published this line as part of a poem in his Memoirs; see Collected Works, vol. 1, p.234. He replaces "transient rainbow" with " evanescent". </p>
            </gloss>
         </note>
         <note xml:id="misc_105" type="description">
            <term id="misc_105-term">travertine</term>
            <gloss id="misc_105-gloss" target="#misc_105-term">
               <p>A form of terrestrial limestone deposited around mineral springs, especially hot springs.</p>
            </gloss>
         </note>
      </listAnnotation>
