      <listNym type="chemical">
         <nym xml:id="chemical_022">
            <form>oxygene</form>
            <def>
               <p>Symbol/formula: O</p>
               <p>Now known as oxygen. Oxygen is a colourless, odourless, tasteless gas essential to living organisms.</p>
            </def>
         </nym>
         <nym xml:id="chemical_017">
            <form>nitrogene</form>
            <def>
               <p>Symbol/formula: N</p>
               <p>Now known as nitrogen. A colourless and odourless gas, nitrogen is non-combustible and non-toxic. Davy also refers to this as azote.</p>
            </def>
         </nym>
         <nym xml:id="chemical_058">
            <form>carbonic acid</form>
            <def>
               <p>Symbol/formula: CO2 or H2CO3 </p>
               <p>Now known as Carbon dioxide (CO2), or a solution of carbon dioxide in water (H2CO3). </p>
            </def>
         </nym>
         <nym xml:id="chemical_078">
            <form>elastic fluid</form>
            <def>
               <p>A descriptive term for a gas, emphasising its elastic quality of spontaneous expansion.</p>
            </def>
         </nym>
         <nym xml:id="chemical_303">
            <form>Chlorine</form>
            <def>
               <p>Symbol/formula: Cl</p>
               <p>Davy named chlorine in 1810 and insisted it was an element and not a compound. </p>
            </def>
         </nym>
         <nym xml:id="chemical_424">
            <form>Iodine</form>
            <def>
               <p>Symbol/formula: I</p>
               <p>An element and the heaviest of the group of stable halogens. Bernard Courtois was the first to isolate the substance. Whilst in Paris Davy investigated the substance, and proved it to be a chemical element describing his results in a paper sent to the Royal Society. This caused disputes between Davy and Joseph Louis Gay-Lussac, who had also been researching the element.</p>
            </def>
         </nym>
         <nym xml:id="chemical_037">
            <form>sulphur</form>
            <def>
               <p>Symbol/formula: S</p>
               <p>Pure sulphur is a tasteless, odourless, brittle solid that is pale yellow in colour, a poor conductor of electricity, and insoluble in water.</p>
            </def>
         </nym>
         <nym xml:id="chemical_362">
            <form>selenium </form>
            <def>
               <p>Symbol/formula: Se</p>
               <p>Chemical element; discovered in 1817 by Jöns Jacob Berzelius.</p>
            </def>
         </nym>
         <nym xml:id="chemical_140">
            <form>charcoal</form>
            <def>
               <p>A lightweight black carbon residue produced by strongly heating wood (or other animal and plant materials) in minimal oxygen to remove all water and volatile constituents.</p>
            </def>
         </nym>
         <nym xml:id="chemical_370">
            <form>cast iron</form>
            <def>
               <p>A class of iron–carbon alloys with a carbon content more than 2% and silicon content around 1-3%.</p>
            </def>
         </nym>
         <nym xml:id="chemical_060">
            <form>manganese</form>
            <def>
               <p>Symbol/formula: Mn</p>
               <p>A hard, brittle, silvery metal, often found in minerals in combination with iron. Manganese was first isolated in the 1770s.</p>
            </def>
         </nym>
         <nym xml:id="chemical_323">
            <form>steel</form>
            <def>
               <p>Steel is an alloy of iron and carbon with improved strength and fracture resistance compared to other forms of iron.</p>
            </def>
         </nym>
         <nym xml:id="chemical_417">
            <form>sulphuric acid</form>
            <def>
               <p>Symbol/formula: H2SO3</p>
               <p>A mineral acid composed of the elements sulphur, oxygen, and hydrogen. It is a colourless, odourless, and viscous liquid that is miscible with water.</p>
            </def>
         </nym>
         <nym xml:id="chemical_081">
            <form>calcareous</form>
            <def>
               <p>Composed of, or containing, lime or limestone.</p>
            </def>
         </nym>
         <nym xml:id="chemical_120">
            <form>shist</form>
            <def>
               <p>Or schist. Any metamorphic rock that can be split into thin layers because of its thin bands of micaceous minerals, with mineral grains.</p>
            </def>
         </nym>
         <nym xml:id="chemical_099">
            <form>greywacke</form>
            <def>
               <p>Greywacke or graywacke is a type of sandstone.</p>
            </def>
         </nym>
         <nym xml:id="chemical_095">
            <form>micaceous shist</form>
            <def>
               <p>A rock composed of mica and quartz.</p>
            </def>
         </nym>
         <nym xml:id="chemical_090">
            <form>limestone</form>
            <def>
               <p>A sedimentary rock composed mainly of calcium carbonate (CaCO3).</p>
            </def>
         </nym>
         <nym xml:id="chemical_505">
            <form>Stalactite</form>
            <def>
               <p>An icicle shaped mineral formation which hands from the ceiling - or protrudes from the sides - of caves. </p>
            </def>
         </nym>
         <nym xml:id="chemical_175">
            <form>bitumen</form>
            <def>
               <p>A sticky, black, highly viscous liquid or semi-solid form of petroleum.</p>
            </def>
         </nym>
         <nym xml:id="chemical_116">
            <form>whinstone</form>
            <def>
               <p>A term used to describe any hard dark-coloured rock, examples of which include igneous rocks and basalt.</p>
            </def>
         </nym>
         <nym xml:id="chemical_148">
            <form>tufa</form>
            <def>
               <p>A variety of limestone formed when carbonate minerals precipitate out of water at ambient temperature.</p>
            </def>
         </nym>
         <nym xml:id="chemical_102">
            <form>quartz</form>
            <def>
               <p>Symbol/formula: SiO2</p>
               <p>A hard, crystalline mineral composed of silica (silicon dioxide).</p>
            </def>
         </nym>
         <nym xml:id="chemical_105">
            <form>basalt</form>
            <def>
               <p>A dark grey to black dense to fine-grained igneous rock that consists of basic plagioclase, augite, and usually magnetite. More than 90% of volcanic rock on earth is basaltic.</p>
            </def>
         </nym>
         <nym xml:id="chemical_363">
            <form>tiburtinum</form>
            <def>
               <p>Carbonate rock, more commonly known as travertine. </p>
            </def>
         </nym>
         <nym xml:id="chemical_397">
            <form>shale</form>
            <def>
               <p>Shale is a fine-grained, clastic sedimentary rock formed from mud that is a mix of flakes of clay minerals and tiny fragments of other minerals, especially quartz and calcite.</p>
            </def>
         </nym>
         <nym xml:id="chemical_007">
            <form>hydrogene</form>
            <def>
               <p>Symbol/formula: H</p>
               <p>Now known as hydrogen. Hydrogen is the lightest element and, at standard conditions, is a gas of diatomic molecules. It is colourless, odourless, tasteless, non-toxic, and highly combustible.</p>
            </def>
         </nym>
         <nym xml:id="chemical_364">
            <form>alluvium</form>
            <def>
               <p>Loose clay, silt, sand, or gravel that has been deposited by running water</p>
            </def>
         </nym>
      </listNym>
